        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3440724351" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer504288922721349738">I&apos;ve read three books by Michael Ende and they&apos;re all brilliant, shining jewels, but this one is the diamond. It&apos;s a story about a very much unhappy child, Bastian, who through a book falls into a magical place where he can have anything he wants, absolutely anything. While doing so, he loses himself again and again before finally finding his true self - and thus he returns, a changed, better person, finally able to love and be loved. So basically Fantastica is Bastian&apos;s catharsis, and what a ca</span>
  <span id="freeText504288922721349738" style="display:none">I've read three books by Michael Ende and they're all brilliant, shining jewels, but this one is the diamond. It's a story about a very much unhappy child, Bastian, who through a book falls into a magical place where he can have anything he wants, absolutely anything. While doing so, he loses himself again and again before finally finding his true self - and thus he returns, a changed, better person, finally able to love and be loved. So basically Fantastica is Bastian's catharsis, and what a catharsis it is: he meets anything he, or you, can imagine. From dragons - not the beastly ones from A Song of Ice and Fire, but the friendly ones - to centaurs, to the Childlike Empress, each one of Ende's creations is both fascinating and enchanting. A truly great book. F-I-V-E stars.</span>
  <a data-text-id="504288922721349738" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
