  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3256335222" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3256335222" />
    <a title="Trish" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3461034-trish"><img alt="Trish" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1588663568p2/3461034.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3256335222?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Trish" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Trish" href="/user/show/3461034-trish">Trish</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9783522202503" href="/book/show/51915151-die-unendliche-geschichte">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3256335222" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2447822566816339687">I was five when my stepfather introduced me to the movie adaptation of this German classic. Shortly afterwards, he took me on a trip to the Bavaria Film Studios where most of the movie was made. I was fascinated by the mighty Pjörnrachzarck (the Rockbiter) as the puppet was huge. But I was even more enchanted when I was allowed to ride on Fuchur (Falkor)!<br/>Sadly, since nobody in my family reads, I never got the book as a kid. Through the years, I came across it again and again and, eventually, als</span>
  <span id="freeText2447822566816339687" style="display:none">I was five when my stepfather introduced me to the movie adaptation of this German classic. Shortly afterwards, he took me on a trip to the Bavaria Film Studios where most of the movie was made. I was fascinated by the mighty Pjörnrachzarck (the Rockbiter) as the puppet was huge. But I was even more enchanted when I was allowed to ride on Fuchur (Falkor)!<br>Sadly, since nobody in my family reads, I never got the book as a kid. Through the years, I came across it again and again and, eventually, also obtained a copy but never read that.<br>To be honest, if it hadn't been for the illustrated edition catching my eye, I might not have read it now.<br>Only recently, I re-watched the movie (after finally buying the DVD/BD) and it's the mark of a truly great movie (despite all possible weaknesses) that manages to immediately invoke the old nostalgia the way it did.<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1586642313i/29276681._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>Bastian Balthasar Bux is a chubby little boy who gets bullied in school and loves to read. That immediately made me like and dislike him (he has a few character traits that aren't too charming but that only made him a "real" boy). *lol* One day, he flees from some of his tormentors and ends up in an antique bookshop where he steals the titular book from the owner. Convinced stealing the book makes it impossible for him to go back home, he hides away in the school's attic and reads the book.<br>In the book, a fantasy world full of weird creatures is in mortal danger. <br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1586642313i/29276682._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>Atréju, a child hunter, is tasked by the Childlike Empress to find out what can save them all. He has to cross all corners of the world, survive many dangers and live through many heartships, encountering different creatures who have advice for him along the way.<br>But the book also connects its reader (Bastian) with the story and soon Bastian finds out that he is meant to save Phantásia.<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1586642313i/29276683._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>It's no secret that he succeeds and then the second part of the book has him enter the very world he saved, reconstructing it, creating different quests and losing one memory after another in exchange for wishes fulfilled. <br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1586642313i/29276684._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1586642313i/29276685._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1586642313i/29276686._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>And that is not the only danger.<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1586642313i/29276687._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>It sounds like a little bit of a mess, maybe, but it really isn't. The core of the story is about the power of telling a tale, of lies and the things we should have said but never did, of wishes and memories; it's about how humanity's world needs stories and how stories need us humans; it's about how we’re all made of stories. And it's a declaration of love to reading itself from a bookworm to all us other bookworms.<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1586642314i/29276688._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Michael Ende has created a masterpiece if you ask me. It's not often that a German author fascinates me this much and he is the only one who has managed to stay with me (with just this one story so far, mind you) all my life (though I have some other books of his). <br><br>The writing style is utterly beautiful, almost hauntingly so. The writing is poetical as well as metaphorical; we get many deeper examinations of human nature that are nevertheless perfect for children - Michael Ende being one of the few authors that seem to have the perfect voice with which to talk to children (without treating them like idiots); we get the perfect worldbuilding that just sucks the reader in; we get the full palette of human emotions - also thanks to the author making us care so deeply for every creature we meet - and breathless action on top of that.<br><br>One more thing I love is how the book has been made. Not just this special edition, but the "ordinary" editions as well. At least the original (German) ones have red and green text (red for Bastian's world, green for Phantásia). Why? Because we ARE the story and we are IN the story, which takes place in two different worlds (at first at least) so the author insisted on this quirky feature in order to show the different layers and it's brilliant of you ask me.<br><br>Then, there is this illustrated edition, which is a thing of beauty (as you can see from the few examples posted above). The artist might not be great at sketching/drawing human faces but he is a master at bringing to life the different quirky creatures and breathtaking places we get to explore while reading the book. There are so many that it was very hard to decide what to show you. Most were full-color drawings of which some were on one full page while others were double-page spreads. And some were just pencil sketches like these two:<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1586642314i/29276689._SY540_.jpg" width="300" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1586642314i/29276690._SX540_.jpg" width="300" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> <br>(these are smaller than the colour drawings and decorate/accompany the text itself). <br><br>I'm glad I finally read this book in its entirety. For anyone interested: yes, the second movie has many elements that also stem from the book. I can see why that was done. After all, if this book was published today, I'm sure we'd get two separate volumes. But I can also see where the producers of the second movie went horribly wrong and thus lost the magic of the first along the way. The first movie, by the way, is by no means perfect - but it's still fantastic.<br>Regardless, as is usually the case, the world between the pages is more colorful, richer and more fulfilling. I really cannot praise this book enough.<br><br><br><br>P.S.: Sorry that I've mostly used the German names for places and characters; I'm just too used to them and those ARE their „real“ names after all. ;P<br><br>P.P.S.: I've learned only yesterday that Fuchur (Falkor) still exists and still is making children happy in the Bavaria Film Studios so I guess I have to go back there as soon as Covid-19 allows it and visit my old friend.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2447822566816339687" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


